1 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
2 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
3 A. The Legislature finds that malicious false reporting of
4 crimes:
5 1. Endangers innocent persons by provoking unwarranted law
6 enforcement action;
7 2. Diverts limited public safety and investigative resources;
8 3. Undermines public trust in emergency response systems; and
9 4. Causes reputational, financial, and psychological harm to
10 persons falsely accused.
11 B. The purpose of this act is to deter malicious false reports
12 while preserving and protecting good-faith reporting of crimes and
13 emergencies.
14 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 21 O.S. 2021, Section 589, as
15 amended by Section 667, Chapter 486, O.S.L. 2025 (21 O.S. Supp.
16 2025, Section 589), is amended to read as follows:
17 Section 589. A. It shall be unlawful to willfully, knowingly
18 and without probable cause make a false report to any person of any
19 crime or circumstances indicating the possibility of crime having
20 been committed, including the unlawful taking of personal property,
21 which report causes or encourages the exercise of police action or
22 investigation. Any person convicted of violating the provisions of
23 this subsection shall be guilty of a misdemeanor punishable by
24 imprisonment in the county jail for not more than ninety (90) days
(Floor Amendments Only) Date and Time Filed:
Untimely Amendment Cycle Extended Secondary Amendment

1 or by a fine of not more than Five Hundred Dollars ($500.00), or by
2 both such fine and imprisonment if the false report accused a
3 person of a misdemeanor. Any person convicted of violating the
4 provisions of this subsection shall be guilty of a felony if the
5 false report accused a person of a felony. The punishments for
6 such misdemeanor or felony shall be the same as the provisions for
7 the offense in the false report.
8 B. It shall be unlawful to willfully, knowingly, and without
9 probable cause communicate false information concerning a missing
10 child to a law enforcement agency that causes or encourages the
11 activation of an AMBER alert warning system. Any person convicted
12 of violating the provisions of this subsection shall be guilty of a
13 Class D3 felony offense punishable by imprisonment as provided for
14 in subsections B through F E of Section 20P of this title, or by a
15 fine of not less than One Thousand Dollars ($1,000.00), or by both
16 such imprisonment and fine and imprisonment.
